node.text: It isn’t easy to defend our planet from asteroids. That’s why we support those who step up to the job.

Star Trek: Voyager's holographic doctor, Robert Picardo, also serves on The Planetary Society Board of Directors. However, he is not the first connection between Star Trek and The Planetary Society. In 1980, the creator of Star Trek, Gene Roddenberry, wrote a letter and sent it out to a Star Trek fans mailing list. In the letter, Gene invited his fans to join us on our mission to explore the cosmos.

Hear the letter as read by Robert Picardo, listen to his Jean-Luc Picard impression, and see inside Bill Nye's office for more Star Trek artifacts on hand at The Planetary Society.

Read the full letter at planetary.org

node.title: A rare letter from Star Trek creator Gene Roddenberry

NASA's Juno mission has gone farther into deep space than any other solar-powered probe. Most spacecraft that far from the Sun need nuclear power to operate, but Juno's three huge solar panels collect enough sunlight to keep it going.

Since arriving in orbit around Jupiter in 2016, the mission has yielded amazing discoveries and extraordinary images, like this one of Jupiter’s complex cloud systems.

(📸: NASA et al.)

Perseverance's first rock collecting attempt on Mars didn't go as planned. The autonomous sampling process went through all of the steps, but in the end, the material didn't make it into the sample tube. 

But hey — Mars is hard. If at first you don't succeed, analyze your data, make a plan, and try, try again. We'll learn a lot from this attempt!

@NASA's Perseverance rover took this image of the sampling site drill hole earlier today.

What's something that you had to try a few times before you got it right?

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech)

#Mars #NASA #space

node.text:
Sixty years ago today, cosmonaut Gherman Titov became the second human to orbit the Earth.

Titov was just 25 years old when he launched aboard the Soviet Vostok 2 mission. He held the record for the youngest person to reach space until last month when @blueorigin's first crewed mission carried Oliver Daemen, 18 years old, to space.

Among his lists of firsts, Titov takes the prize for the first person to experience space sickness and the first person to sleep in space.

If you could go to space, what first would you want to be known for?

(Image: Kosmicheskaya programma SSSR)

#OTD #space #science

node.text:
Earth: I'm awesome. 🤗
Titan: But I have rain, lakes, and a thick atmosphere, too! 
Earth: Isn't your rain, like, methane or something?
Titan: Still rain. 🌧
Earth: Well, I have life, so —
Titan: Psh. You don't know me!

Titan, Saturn's largest moon, is almost the size of Mars. It is the only other place in the solar system with liquid on its surface and the only moon with a thick atmosphere. Sounds like a tantalizing destination to search for life!

What do you think is the most surprising thing about Titan?

This color-composite of Titan was made from images taken by @NASA's Cassini spacecraft on January 12, 2013. During this period, a large ice cloud system had formed over the moon's south pole. 

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech/SSI/Cassini Imaging Team/Jason Major)

#Saturn #moon #space

Target acquired. Now to grab a sample!

@NASA's Perseverance rover is on a mission to collect and cache samples from Mars for a later return mission to Earth. Today Perseverance begins its first sampling. If it goes well, Perseverance will become the only spacecraft in history to gather a rock core on another planet and seal it for its return to Earth.

Good luck, Percy!

(Vid: NASA)

#Mars #rockcollection #NASA

node.text:
Today's the 10th anniversary of the launch of @NASA's Juno mission to Jupiter!

Juno launched aboard a United Launch Alliance Atlas V rocket from Cape Canaveral Air Force Station on August 5, 2011. The journey to Jupiter took Juno about five years, but it was so worth it. We've learned a lot about the planet since then, not to mention all of the gorgeous images of our solar system's largest planet.

Which Juno images are your favorites?
a.) Close-up storms
b.) Jupiter's moons
c.) Jupiter at a distance
d.) I'm just in it for the data.

(📸 : NASA/Tony Gray and Don Kight)

#OTD #Jupiter #NASA

node.text:
The Perseid meteor shower peaks next week. 

What's your favorite meteor shower memory? ☄️

Meteor showers happen when the Earth passes through the debris field left behind by a comet or asteroid. Comet 109P/Swift-Tuttle is the litterbug behind the annual Perseid meteor shower. This image of Swift-Tuttle was taken in 1992. The comet won't return to the inner solar system again until 2125.

The 2021 Perseid meteor shower peaks on the night of August 11 and the morning of August 12. You may also see meteors a few days before and after the 11th. To watch, go to the darkest place you can, let your eyes adjust for several minutes, and then look directly overhead.

(📸 : NASA)

#meteor #space #science

node.text:
NASA's Perseverance rover is getting ready to take its first sample of Martian rock!

Before the rover can gather its first rock core, Percy has to search its surroundings for a good target. The rover scoured the crust off of this rock to see what lies underneath. In the coming days, it will gather a sample from the rocks nearby.

This image was taken on August 2nd with the camera at the end of the rover's robotic arm. We're excited to see Perseverance in action!

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech)

#Mars #NASA #space

node.text:
Nobody:
Ganymede: Not to brag, but I'm kind of a big deal.

@NASA's Juno spacecraft got this image of Ganymede, a moon of Jupiter, on July 20th. Ganymede is the largest moon in the solar system and the only moon (that we know of) with its own magnetic field. 

What do you think our solar system's moons would brag about if they could talk?

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech/SwRI/MSSS/Kevin M. Gill (@apoapsys))

#Jupiter #Moon #space

node.text:
Here's your daily dose of Earth from space. Side effects may include: wonder, science, and perspective on human existence. If your wonder lasts for more than 6 hours, don't worry about it. You're fine. 🌎

This image of Chile was taken by our crowdfunded LightSail 2 spacecraft on February 17, 2020. North is at right. The Uyuni Salt Flat in Bolivia can be seen at the top center. The sail appears slightly curved due to the spacecraft's 185-degree fisheye camera lens.

#space #Earth #science

node.text:
Have you seen a Moon rock in a museum before?

The Apollo 15 crew brought more than 77 kilograms (170 pounds) of lunar rock and soil samples back to Earth, including the Genesis Rock. At around 4.1 billion years old, it is one of the oldest rocks ever studied by scientists.

The Genesis Rock was a piece of the Moon’s primordial crust. @NASA chose the Apollo 15 landing site in the hopes that the crew would find this type of rock.

For size comparison, the cube placed next to the rock in these images is 2.5 cm (1 in) across.

Fifty years ago today, Commander David Scott became the first astronaut to drive on the Moon!

Apollo 15's Lunar Rover traveled about 27 km (17 mi) during the mission and paved the way for Apollo 16 and 17's Lunar Rovers. All three "Moon buggies" were left behind on the Moon and are still there to this day.
